The following is a list of algorithms along with one-line descriptions for each.Combinatorial algorithmsGeneral combinatorial algorithms* Brents algorithm: finds cycles in iterations using only two iterators* cycle-finding algorithm: finds cycles in iterations* algorithm: solve the marriage problem* number generators (uniformly distributed):** Blum Shub** Fibonacci generator** congruential generator** twisterGraph algorithms* algorithm: Graph coloring algorithm.* algorithm: convert a bipartite graph to a cardinality matching* algorithm: algorithm for finding a matching* Prfer coding: conversion between a labeled tree and its sequence* off-line least common ancestors algorithm: compute common ancestors for pairs of nodes in a tree* Topological sort: finds linear order of nodes (e.g. jobs) based on their dependencies.Graph drawing* Force-based algorithms (also known as force-directed algorithms or spring-based algorithm)* layoutNetwork theory* Network analysis** Link analysis*** algorithm: detect communities in complex systems*** Web link analysis**** Topic Search (HITS) (also known as and authorities)**** PageRank**** TrustRank**** PRW, PFW* networks** algorithm: is a polynomial algorithm for computing the flow in a network.** algorithm: implementation of FordFulkerson** algorithm: computes the maximum flow in a graph** algorithm:  a Monte Carlo method to compute the cut of a connected graph** algorithm: computes a maximum flow in a graphRouting* algorithm (also known as ChuLiu/Edmondss algorithm): find maximum or minimum branchings* minimum spanning tree: algorithms for computing the minimum spanning tree of a set of points in the plane* path problem: find a simple path of maximum length in a given graph* spanning tree** algorithm** algorithm** algorithm** algorithm* Minimal Spanning Switch say, for a exchange* path problem** algorithm: computes shortest paths in a weighted graph (where some of the edge weights may be negative)** algorithm: computes shortest paths in a graph with non-negative edge weights** algorithm: solves the pairs shortest path problem in a weighted, directed graph** algorithm: All pairs shortest path algorithm in sparse weighted directed graph** methods: an algorithm that computes a locally shortest paths in a graph* salesman problem** algorithm** neighbour algorithm* Warnsdorffs algorithm: A heuristic method for solving the Tour problem.Search* A*: special case of best-first search that uses heuristics to improve speed* B*: a best-first graph search algorithm that finds the least-cost path from a given initial node to any goal node (out of one or more possible goals)* Backtracking: abandon partial solutions when they are found not to satisfy a complete solution* search: is a heuristic search algorithm that is an optimization of search that reduces its memory requirement* stack search: integrates backtracking with search* search: traverses a graph in the order of likely importance using a queue* search: find the shortest path from an initial vertex to a goal vertex in a directed graph* filter: a constant time and memory check to see whether a given element exists in a set. May return a false positive, but never a false negative.* search: traverses a graph level by level* D*: an heuristic search algorithm* search: traverses a graph branch by branch* algorithm: A special case of A* for which no heuristic function is used* Problem Solver: a seminal theorem-proving algorithm intended to work as a universal problem solver machine.* deepening depth-first search (IDDFS): a state space search strategy* breadth-first search (also known as Lex-BFS): a linear time algorithm for ordering the vertices of a graph* search: a tree search that finds the lowest cost route where costs vary* SSS*: state space search traversing a game tree in a best-first fashion similar to that of the A* search algorithmSubgraphs* algorithm: a technique for finding cliques in an undirected graph* connected components** CheriyanMehlhorn/Gabow algorithm** algorithm** algorithmSequence algorithmsApproximate matching* algorithm: fuzzy algorithm that determines if strings are approximately equal.* algorithms** Soundex: a Soundex refinement which allows matching of Slavic and Germanic surnames** Metaphone: an improvement on Metaphone** Rating Approach: a phonetic algorithm developed by Western Airlines** Metaphone: an algorithm for indexing words by their sound, when pronounced in English** NYSIIS: algorithm, improves on Soundex** Soundex: a phonetic algorithm for indexing names by sound, as pronounced in English* metrics: compute a similarity or dissimilarity (distance) score between two pairs of text strings** distance compute a distance measure between two strings, improves on distance** coefficient (also known as the Dice coefficient): a similarity measure related to the index** distance: sum number of positions which are different** distance:  is a measure of similarity between two strings** Levenshtein edit distance: compute a metric for the amount of difference between two sequences* search: search for text when the exact syntax or spelling of the target object is not precisely knownItem search* search: finds an item in an unsorted list* algorithm: finds the kth largest item in a list* lists** search algorithm: locates an item in a sorted list** search technique: search a sorted array using a divide and conquer algorithm that narrows down possible locations with the aid of numbers** search (also called block search)** Predictive search: binary-like search which factors in magnitude of search term versus the high and low values in the search.  Sometimes called dictionary search or interpolated search.** binary search: an optimization of the classic binary search algorithm* search: a technique for finding the minimum or maximum of a function that is either strictly increasing and then strictly decreasing or vice versaMerging* Simple Merge algorithm* k-way Merge algorithm* Union (merge, with elements on the output not repeated)Permutations* shuffle (also known as the Knuth shuffle): randomly shuffle a finite set* algorithm: constructs a pair of tableaux from a permutation* algorithm (also known as the JohnsonTrotter algorithm): generate permutations by transposing elementsSequence alignment* time warping: measure similarity between two sequences which may vary in time or speed* algorithm: finds the least cost alignment between two sequences, as measured by their distance* algorithm: find global alignment between two sequences* algorithm: find local sequence alignmentSorting* Exchange Sorts** sort: for each pair of indices, swap the items if out of order** sort** sort** sort** sort** Quicksort: divide list into two, with all items on the first list coming before all items on the second list.; then sort the two lists. Often the method of choice* Humorous or ineffective** Bogosort** sort* Hybrid** Flashsort** Introsort: begin with quicksort and switch to heapsort when the recursion depth exceeds a certain level** Timsort: adaptative algorithm derived from merge sort and insertion sort. Used in Python >2.3 and Java SE 7.* Insertion sorts** sort: determine where the current item belongs in the list of sorted ones, and insert it there** sort** sorting** sort: an attempt to improve insertion sort** sort (binary tree sort): build binary tree, then traverse it to create sorted list** sort: in-place with theoretically optimal number of writes* Merge sorts** sort: sort the first and second half of the list separately, then merge the sorted lists** sort* Non-comparison sorts** sort** sort** Burstsort: build a compact, cache efficient trie and then traverse it to create sorted output** sort** sort** sort: variant of Bucket sort which takes advantage of hierarchical structure** sort: sorts strings letter by letter* Selection sorts** Heapsort: convert the list into a heap, keep removing the largest element from the heap and adding it to the end of the list** sort: pick the smallest of the remaining elements, add it to the end of the sorted list** Smoothsort* Other** sorter** sorting** Topological sort* Unknown class** SamplesortSubsequences*algorithm: finds maximum sub-array of any size*common subsequence problem: Find the longest subsequence common to all sequences in a set of sequences*increasing subsequence problem: find the longest increasing subsequence of a given sequence*common supersequence problem: Find the shortest supersequence that contains two or more sequences as subsequencesSubstrings* common substring problem:  find the longest string (or strings) that is a substring (or are substrings) of two or more strings* search** string matching algorithm: trie based algorithm for finding all substring matches to any of a finite set of strings** string search algorithm: amortized linear (sublinear in most times) algorithm for substring search** algorithm: Simplification of BoyerMoore** algorithm: substring search which bypasses reexamination of matched characters** string search algorithm: searches multiple patterns efficiently** string matching algorithm: a variant of the BoyerMoore* algorithm: a linear-time, algorithm for constructing treesComputational mathematicsAbstract algebra* search: a recursive algorithm for determining roots of polynomials defined over a finite field* algorithm: computing a base and generating set (BSGS) of a group* algorithm: Procedure for generating cosets.Computer algebra* algorithm: finds a basis* algorithm: factor polynomials over finite fields* F4 algorithm: finds a Grbner basis (also mentions the F5 algorithm)* algorithm: find sums of hypergeometric terms that are themselves hypergeometric terms* completion algorithm: for rewriting rule systems* division algorithm: for polynomials in several indeterminates* kangaroo algorithm (also known as Pollards lambda algorithm ): an algorithm for solving the discrete logarithm problem* long division: an algorithm for dividing a polynomial by another polynomial of