1965
__NOTOC__Year 1965 (MCMLXV) was a year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the calendar. Events  January * 1 &ndash; The ship SS Catala is driven onto the beach in Shores, Washington, stranding her.* 4 &ndash; U.S. President B. Johnson proclaims his Society during his of the Union Address.* 9 &ndash; The Cadet College formally opens for academic activities in East Pakistan (now Bangladesh).* 12 &ndash; Beach Murders: The bodies of two 15-year-olds, Christine Sharrock and Marianne Schmidt, are found at Beach, Sydney.* 14 &ndash; The Prime Minister of Ireland and the Taoiseach of the of Ireland meet for the first time in 43 years.* 19 &ndash; The unmanned 2 is launched on a suborbital test of various spacecraft systems.* 20 &ndash; B. Johnson is sworn in for his own full term as President.* 26 &ndash; Anti-Hindi agitations break out in India, because of which Hindi does not get National Language status and remains one of the 23 official languages of India.* 30 &ndash; State funeral of Sir Winston Churchill takes place with the largest assembly of statesmen in the world until the 2005 funeral of John Paul II.() February File:Flag of Canada.svg|thumb|180px|The newly adopted of Canada* 6 &ndash; Sir Matthews plays his final First Division game, at the record age of 50 years and 5 days.* 12 &ndash; African and Malagasy Common Organization (OCAM) (Organization Commune Africaine et Malgache) formed as successor to the Afro-Malagasy Union for Economic Cooperation (Union Africaine et Malgache de Cooperation Economique; UAMCE), formerly the African and Malagasy Union (Union Africaine et Malgache; UAM)).* 15 &ndash; A new red and white maple leaf design is inaugurated as the of Canada, replacing the Flag and the Red Ensign.* 18 &ndash; Gambia becomes independent from the Kingdom.* 20** 8 crashes into the Moon, after a successful mission of photographing possible landing sites for the program astronauts.** Hayri rgpl forms the new (interim) government of Turkey (29th government)* 22 &ndash; A new, revised, color production of and Hammersteins Cinderella airs on CBS. Ann Warren makes her TV debut in the title role. The show becomes an annual tradition. March * 2 &ndash; The Sound of Music premieres at the Rivoli Theater in New York City.* 7 &ndash; Bloody Sunday: Some 200 Alabama State Troopers clash with 525 civil rights demonstrators in Alabama.* 8 &ndash; War: Some 3,500 States Marines arrive in Vietnam, becoming the first American combat troops in Vietnam.* 9 &ndash; The second attempt to march from Selma to Alabama, under the leadership of Luther King, Jr., stops at the bridge that was the site of Bloody Sunday, to hold a prayer service and return to Selma, in obedience to a court restraining order.  supremacists beat up white Universalist minister J. Reeb later that day in Selma.* 10** Goldie, a Zoo golden eagle, is recaptured 12 days after her escape.** Engagement announced between Margriet of the Netherlands and van Vollenhoven, who will become the first commoner and the first Dutchman to marry into the Royal Family.* 11 &ndash; White Universalist minister J. Reeb, beaten by supremacists in Alabama on 9 following the second march from Selma, dies in a hospital in Alabama.*15 -- President LBJ makes his We Shall Overcome speech.* 16 &ndash; Police clash with 600 SNCC marchers in Alabama.* 17** In Alabama, 1,600 civil rights marchers demonstrate at the Courthouse.** In response to the events of March 7 and 9 in Selma, Alabama, President B. Johnson sends a bill to Congress that forms the basis for the Voting Rights Act of 1965.  It is passed by the Senate May 26, the House July 10, and signed into law by President Johnson Aug. 6.* 18** Cosmonaut Leonov, leaving his spacecraft 2 for 12 minutes, becomes the first person to walk in space.** A States federal judge rules that SCLC has the lawful right to march to Alabama to petition for redress of grievances.* 19 &ndash; The wreck of the Georgiana, reputed to have been the most powerful Confederate cruiser ever built and owned by the real Butler, is discovered off the of Palms, Carolina, by teenage diver Lee Spence, exactly 102 years after she was sunk with a million dollar cargo while attempting to run past the Union blockade into Charleston.* 20** Poupe de cire, poupe de son, sung by Gall (music and lyrics by Gainsbourg) wins the Song Contest 1965 for Luxembourg.** The War of 1965 begins.* 21** program: NASA launches 9, which is the last in a series of unmanned lunar probes.** Luther King, Jr. leads 3,200 rights activists in the third march from Selma, Alabama to the capitol in Montgomery.* 22 &ndash; Ceauescu becomes the first secretary of the Communist Party.* 23 &ndash; 3: NASA launches the States first 2-person crew (Grissom, John Young) into orbit.* 25 &ndash; Luther King, Jr. and 25,000 civil rights activists successfully end the 4-day march from Selma, Alabama, to the capitol in Montgomery.* 30** Funeral services are held for Detroit homemaker Liuzzo, who was shot dead by 4 Klansmen as she drove marchers back to Selma at night after the civil rights march.** Second ODECA charter, signed on 12 December 1962, effective. April * 3 &ndash; The worlds first space nuclear power reactor, SNAP-10A, is launched by the United States from Vandenberg AFB, California.  The reactor operates for 43 days and remains in Earth orbit.* 5 &ndash; At the Academy Awards, My Fair Lady wins 8 Academy Awards, including Best Picture and Best Director. Harrison wins an Oscar for Best Actor. Mary Poppins takes home 5 Oscars. Andrews wins an Award for Best Actress, for her portrayal in the role.  Brothers receives 2 Oscars including Song, Chim Cher-ee.* 6** The Early Bird satellite is launched. It becomes operational 2 and is placed in commercial service in June.** The British Government announced the cancellation of the TSR-2 aircraft project.* 9** The West German parliament extends the of limitations on Nazi crimes.** In Texas, the Harris County Domed Stadium (more commonly known as the Astrodome) opens.** The 100th anniversary of the end of the Civil War is observed.** Brown and the Peanuts Gang appear on the cover of Magazine.* 11 &ndash; The Sunday tornado outbreak of 1965: An estimated 51 tornadoes (47 confirmed) hit in 6 Midwestern states, killing between 256 to 271 people and injuring some 1,500 more.* 14 &ndash; In Cold Blood killers Hickock and Perry Smith, convicted of murdering 4 members of the Clutter family of Kansas, are executed by hanging at the Kansas State Penitentiary for Men in Kansas.* 17 &ndash; The first SDS march against the Vietnam War draws 25,000 protestors to Washington, DC.* 18 &ndash; Consecration of Clement of Ohrid Macedonian Orthodox Cathedral in Toronto, Canada.* 21 &ndash; The NY Worlds Fair in Meadows, NY, reopens.* 23 &ndash; The Way officially opens.* 24** The Yerevan demonstrations start in Yerevan, demanding recognition of the Genocide.** The bodies of Portuguese opposition politician Delgado and his secretary Arajaryr Moreira de Campos are found in a forest near Villanueva del Fresno, Spain (they were killed 12).** In the Republic, officers and civilians loyal to deposed President Bosch mutiny against the right-wing junta running the country, setting up a government.  Forces loyal to the deposed military-imposed government stage a countercoup the next day, and civil war breaks out, although the new government retains its hold on power.* 25 &ndash; On this Sunday morning teenage sniper Michael Clark kills three and wounds others shooting at cars from a hilltop along 101 just south of California. Sixteen year old Clark kills himself as police rush hilltop.* 28** U.S. troops are sent to the Republic by President B. Johnson, for the stated purpose of protecting U.S. citizens and preventing an alleged Communist takeover of the country, thus thwarting the possibility of another Cuba.** War: Minister of Australia Menzies announces that the country will substantially increase its number of troops in Vietnam, supposedly at the request of the Saigon government (it is later revealed that Menzies had asked the leadership in Saigon to send the request at the behest of the Americans).* 29 &ndash; Australia announces that it is sending an infantry battalion to support the Vietnam government. May * 1** Bob Askin replaces Renshaw as Premier of South Wales.** The of Dong-Yin occurs as a conflict between Taiwan and the Republic of China.** Liverpool wins the FA Cup Final, beating Leeds Utd 21.* 5 &ndash; Forty men burn their draft cards at the of California, Berkeley, and a coffin is marched to the Berkeley Draft Board.* 6 &ndash; A tornado outbreak near the Cities in Minnesota kills 13 and injures 683.* 12** Germany and Israel establish diplomatic relations.** The Italian liner T/S Michelangelo enters into service.* 13 &ndash; A West German of appeals condemns the behavior of ex-defense minister Franz Joseph Strauss during the scandal.* 21 &ndash; The largest teach-in to date begins at California, attended by 30,000.* 22 &ndash; The first skateboard championship is held.  In addition, several hundred Vietnam War protesters in Berkeley, California, march to the Draft Board again to burn 19 more cards. Johnson is hung in effigy.* 25 &ndash; Ali knocks out Liston in the first round of their championship rematch with the Phantom Punch at the Maine Civic Center in Lewiston.* 29 &ndash; A accident in Dhanbad, India kills 274.* 31 &ndash; Racing driver Clark wins the 500, and later wins the One world driving championship in the same year. June File:FIU Green Library.JPG|right|thumb|170px|Green Library at International University in FL* 1** International University is founded in FL.** A coal mine explosion in Fukuoka, Japan kills 237.* 2 &ndash; War: The first contingent of Australian combat troops arrives in Vietnam.* 3 &ndash; 4: Astronaut Higgins White makes the first U.S. walk.* 7 &ndash; A mining accident in Kakanj, and Herzegovina, results in 128 deaths.* 10 &ndash; War &ndash; of Dong Xoai: About 1,500 Vietcong mount a mortar attack on Xoai, overrunning its military headquarters and the adjoining militia compound.* 16 &ndash; A planned anti-war protest at Pentagon becomes a teach-in, with demonstrators distributing 50,000 leaflets in and around the building.* 19 &ndash; Boumdiennes Revolutionary Council ousts Ben Bella, in a bloodless coup in Algeria.* 20 &ndash; Police in Algiers break up demonstrations by people who have taken to the streets chanting slogans in support of deposed President Bella.* 22 &ndash; The on Basic Relations between Japan and the Republic of Korea is signed in Tokyo.* 25 &ndash; A U.S. Air Force Boeing C135-A bound for Okinawa crashes just after takeoff at El Toro in County, California, killing all 85 on board. July * July &ndash; Commonwealth secretariat created.* 14 &ndash; U.S. spacecraft 4 flies by Mars, becoming the first spacecraft to return images from the Red Planet.* 15 &ndash; Greek Prime minister George Papandreou and his government are dismissed by King Constantine II.* 16 &ndash; The Blanc Tunnel is inaugurated by presidents Saragat and de Gaulle.* 24 &ndash; War:  Four F-4C Phantoms escorting a bombing raid at Kang Chi are targeted by missiles, in the first such attack against American planes in the war. One is shot down and the other 3 sustain damage.* 25 &ndash; Dylan elicits controversy among folk purists by going electric at the Folk Festival.* 26 &ndash; The Maldives receive full independence from Great Britain.* 27 &ndash; Heath becomes Leader of the British Conservative Party.* 28 &ndash; War: U.S. President B. Johnson announces his order to increase the number of States troops in Vietnam from 75,000 to 125,000, and to more than double the number of men drafted per month - from 17,000 to 35,000.* 29 &ndash; War: The first 4,000 Airborne Division paratroopers arrive in Vietnam, landing at Ranh Bay.* 30 &ndash; on Poverty: U.S. President B. Johnson signs the Security Act of 1965 into law, establishing Medicare and Medicaid. August * 1 &ndash; Cigarette advertising is banned on television.* 6 &ndash; U.S. President B. Johnson signs the Rights Act of 1965 into law.* 7 &ndash; Abdul Rahman, Minister of Malaysia, recommends the expulsion of Singapore from the of Malaysia, negotiating its separation with Kuan Yew, Prime Minister of Singapore.* 9** Singapore is expelled from the Federation of Malaysia, which recognizes it as a sovereign nation.  Kuan Yew announces Singapores independence and assumes the position of Prime Minister of the new island nation.** An explosion at an Arkansas missile plant kills 53.** Indonesian president Sukarno collapses in public.* 11 &ndash; The Riots begin in Angeles, California.* 13 &ndash; The rock group Airplane debuts at the Matrix in Francisco, California and begins to appear there regularly.* 15 &ndash; Beatles perform the first stadium concert in the history of rock, playing at Stadium in York.* 18 &ndash; War &ndash; Starlite: 5,500 States Marines destroy a Cong stronghold on the Van Tuong peninsula in Ngai Province, in the first major American ground battle of the war. The Marines were tipped-off by a Viet Cong deserter who said that there was an attack planned against the U.S. base at Lai.* 19 &ndash; At the Auschwitz trial in Frankfurt, 66 ex-SS personnel receive sentences, 15 others smaller ones.* 20 &ndash; Myrick Daniels, an Episcopal seminarian from New Hampshire, is murdered in Hayneville, Alabama while working in the civil rights movement.* 21 &ndash; 5 (Cooper, Conrad) is launched on the first 1-week flight, as well as the first test of cells for electrical power.* 30** Stengel announces his retirement after 55 years in baseball.** musician Dylan releases his influential album 61 Revisited, featuring the song a Rolling Stone.** An avalanche buries a dam construction site at Saas-Fee, Switzerland killing 90 workers.* 31 &ndash; President Johnson signs a law penalizing the burning of draft cards with up to 5 years in prison and a $1,000 fine. September * 2 &ndash; Pakistani troops enter the Indian sector of Kashmir, while Indian troops try to invade Lahore.* 6 &ndash; Republic Of Pakistan observes its Defence day.* 7** The Republic of China announces that it will reinforce its troops on the Indian border.** War: In a follow-up to Augusts Starlite, States Marines and Vietnamese forces initiate Operation Piranha on the Batangan Peninsula,  south of the Chu Lai Marine base.* 8 &ndash; India opens 2 additional fronts against Pakistan.* 9** Koufax pitches a game in a baseball match against the Cubs. The opposing pitcher, Hendley, allows only 1 run, which is unearned.** U.N. Secretary General Thant negotiates with Pakistan President Ayub Khan.** Thant recommends China for Nations membership.** Betsy roars ashore near Orleans, Louisiana with winds of , causing 76 deaths and $1.42 billion in damage. The storm is the first hurricane to cause $1 billion in unadjusted damages, giving it the nickname Billion Dollar Betsy. It is the last major hurricane to strike New Orleans until Katrina 40 years later.* 13 &ndash; The Congress of Arab Countries begins in Casablanca; Bourguiba of Tunisia boycotts the meeting.* 14 &ndash; The fourth and final period of the Vatican Council opens.* 15 &ndash; Mary Poppins comes out in theaters in France.* 16** China protests against Indian provocations in its border region.** In Iraq, Prime Minister Abd ar-Razzaqs attempted coup fails.* 17 &ndash; King II of Greece forms a new government with Prime Minister Stephanopoulos, in an attempt to end a 2-year-old political crisis.* 18** In Denmark, Srensen shoots 4 policemen in pursuit; he is apprehended the same day.** Ikeya-Seki is first sighted by Japanese astronomers.** Soviet Premier Kosygin invites the leaders of India and Pakistan to meet in the Union to negotiate.* 22 &ndash; Radio Peking announces that Indian troops have dismantled their equipment on the Chinese side of the border.* 24** Fighting resumes between Indian and Pakistani troops.** The British governor of Aden cancels the constitution and takes direct control of the protectorate, due to the bad security situation.* 25 &ndash; The Tom & Jerry cartoon series makes its world broadcast premiere on CBS.* 27 &ndash; The largest tanker ship at the time, Tokyo Maru, is launched in Yokohama, Japan.* 28 &ndash; Castro announces that anyone who wants to can emigrate to the States.* 28 &ndash; Volcano in Luzon, Philippines, erupts, killing hundreds.* 30** The Indonesian army, led by General Suharto, crushes an alleged communist coup attempt (see to the New Order and September Movement).** Classic family sci-fi show Thunderbirds debuts on ITV. October * 3** Castro announces that Guevara has resigned and left the country.** U.S. President B. Johnson signs an immigration bill which abolishes quotas based on origin.* 4** At least 150 killed when a commuter train derails at the outskirts of Durban, KwaZulu-Natal, Africa.** Prime minister Smith of Rhodesia and Bottomley of the of Nations begin negotiations in London.** Paul VI visits the United States.   He appears for a Mass in Yankee Stadium and makes a speech at the Nations.** The of California, Irvine opens its doors.* 5 &ndash; Pakistan severs relations with Malaysia because of their disagreement in the UN.* 6 &ndash; Brady, a 27-year-old stock clerk from Hyde in Cheshire, is arrested for allegedly hacking to death (with a hatchet) 17-year-old apprentice electrician Edward Evans at a house on the Hattersley estate.* 7 &ndash; Seven Japanese fishing boats are sunk off Guam by super typhoon Carmen; 209 are killed.* 8** The Indonesian army instigates the arrest and execution of communists which last until March 1966 (see killings of 196566).** The Olympic Committee admits Germany as a member.** The Office Tower opens in London.* 9** University presents the map.** A brigade of Korean soldiers arrive in Vietnam.* 10 &ndash; The first group of Cuban refugees travels to the U.S.* 12** Borten forms a government in Norway.** The U.N. General Council recommends that the Kingdom try everything to stop a rebellion in Rhodesia.* 13 &ndash; Congo President Kasavubu fires Prime Minister Tshombe and forms a provisional government, with Kimba in a leading position.* 15 &ndash; War: The Worker Movement stages an anti-war protest in Manhattan. One draft card burner is arrested, the first under the new law.* 16** Police find a girls body on Moor near Oldham in Lancashire. The body is quickly identified as that of 10-year-old Ann Downey, who disappeared on Day the previous year from a fairground in the Ancoats area of Manchester. Brady, arrested for the murder of a 17-year-old man in nearby Hattersley, is charged with murdering Lesley, as is his 23-year-old girlfriend Hindley.** Anti-war protests draw 100,000 in 80 U.S. cities and around the world.* 17 &ndash; The Worlds Fair at Flushing Meadows, NY, closes.  Due to financial losses, some of the projected site park improvements fail to materialize.* 18 &ndash; The Indonesian government outlaws the Party of Indonesia.* 20 &ndash; Erhard is re-elected Chancellor of Germany (he had first been elected in 1963).* 21** Ikeya-Seki approaches perihelion, passing 450,000 kilometers from the sun.** The OAU meets in Accra, Ghana.* 22** French authors Andr Figueras and Laurent are fined for their comments against De Gaulle.** African countries demand that the Kingdom use force to prevent Rhodesia from declaring unilateral independence.** Colonel Soglo stages a second coup in Dahomey.* 24**British Prime Minister Wilson and Commonwealth Secretary Bottomley travel to Rhodesia for negotiations.**British police find the decomposed body of a boy on Moor.* 25 &ndash; The Union declares its support of African countries in case Rhodesia unilaterally declares independence.* 26** Anti-government demonstrations occur in the Republic.** Police discover the body of Likens in Indianapolis, Indiana.* 27** Brazilian president de Alencar Castelo Branco removes power from parliament, legal courts and opposition parties.** Demirel of AP forms the new government of Turkey (30th government)* 28** French Minister de Murville travels to Moscow.** Paul VI announces that the council has decided that Jews are not collectively responsible for the killing of Christ.** In Louis, Missouri, the -tall parabolic steel Arch is completed.** Ben Barka, a Moroccan politician, is kidnapped in Paris and never seen again.* 29** Brady and Hindley appear in court, charged with the murders of Edward Evans (17), Lesley Ann Downey (10), and John Kilbride (12).** An 80-kiloton nuclear device is detonated at Island, Alaska as part of the Uniform program, code-named Project Long Shot.* 30** War: Near Nang, States Marines repel an intense attack by Cong forces, killing 56 guerrillas. A sketch of Marine positions is found on the dead body of a 13-year-old Vietnamese boy who sold drinks to the Marines the day before.** In DC, a pro-Vietnam War march draws 25,000. November * 1 &ndash; A trolleybus plunges into the Nile at Cairo killing 74 passengers.* 2** Republican Lindsay is elected mayor of York City.** Quaker Morrison, 32, sets himself on fire in front of Pentagon.* 3 &ndash; French President De Gaulle announces that he will stand for re-election.* 5 &ndash; law is announced in Rhodesia. The UN General Assembly accepts British intent to use force against Rhodesia if necessary by a vote of 829.* 6 &ndash; Freedom Flights begin: Cuba and the States formally agree to start an airlift for Cubans who want to go to the United States (by 1971 250,000 Cubans take advantage of this program).* 7 &ndash; Pillsburys world-famous mascot, the Doughboy, is created.* 8** War &ndash; Hump: The Airborne is ambushed by over 1,200 Cong.** The Indian Ocean Territory is created, consisting of Archipelago, Aldabra, Farquhar and Roches islands (on June 23, 1976 Aldabra, Farquhar and Des Roches are returned to the Seychelles).** The (Abolition of Death Penalty) Act 1965 is given Royal Assent, suspending the penalty for murder in the United Kingdom; renewal of the Act in 1969 made the abolition permanent.** The opera of our Lives debuts on NBC.* 9** Blackout of 1965: Several states (VT, NH, MA, CT, RI, NY and portions of NJ) and parts of Canada are hit by a series of blackouts lasting up to 13 hours.** War: In York City, 22-year-old Worker Movement member Allen LaPorte sets himself on fire in front of the Nations building in protest of the war.* 11** In Rhodesia (modern-day Zimbabwe), the white-minority government of Smith unilaterally declares independence.** Airlines Flight 227 a 727-22, crashes short of the runway and catches fire at Lake City International Airport in Lake City, Utah. 43 out of 91 passengers and crew perish.* 12 &ndash; A UN Security Council resolution (voted 100) recommends that other countries not recognize independent Rhodesia.* 13 &ndash; The SS Yarmouth Castle burns and sinks  off Nassau, with the loss of 90 lives.* 14 &ndash; Vietnam War &ndash; of the Ia Drang: In the Drang Valley of the Central Highlands in Vietnam, the first major engagement of the war between regular States and Vietnamese forces begins.* 15 &ndash; U.S. racer Breedlove sets a new speed record of .* 16 &ndash; program: The Union launches the 3 space probe from Baikonur, Kazakhstan toward Venus (on March 1, 1966 it became the first spacecraft to reach the surface of another planet).* 20 &ndash; The UN Security Council recommends that all states stop trading with Rhodesia.* 21 &ndash; Mathieu sings on Frances Tl-Dimanche and begins her successful singing career (Dimanche is French for Sunday).* 22** of La Mancha opens in a Greenwich Village theatre in New York and eventually becomes one of the greatest musical hits of all time, winning a Award for its star, Kiley.** Dylan weds Lowndes.** UNDP established as a specialized agency of the Nations.* 23 &ndash; Soviet general Mikhail Kazakov assumes command of the Pact.* 24 &ndash; Congolese lieutenant general Mobutu ousts Kasavubu and declares himself president.* 26 &ndash; At the Hammaguira launch facility in the Desert, France launches a Diamant-A rocket with its first satellite, Asterix-1 on board, becoming the third country to enter space.* 27** Tens of thousands of Vietnam War protesters picket the House, then march on the Monument.** War: Pentagon tells U.S. President B. Johnson that if planned major sweep operations to neutralize Cong forces during the next year are to succeed, the number of American troops in Vietnam will have to be increased from 120,000 to 400,000.* 28 &ndash; Vietnam War: In response to U.S. President B. Johnsons call for more flags in Vietnam, Philippines President-elect Marcos announces he will send troops to help fight in Vietnam.* 29 &ndash; The Canadian satellite 2 is launched. December * 1 &ndash; The Security Force is established in India as a special force to guard the borders.* 3** The first British aid flight arrives in Lusaka; Zambia had asked for British help against Rhodesia.** Members of the of African Unity decide to sever diplomatic relations with the Kingdom, unless the British government ends the rebellion of Rhodesia by mid-December.** The Beatles release Soul.* 5 &ndash; de Gaulle is re-elected as French president with 10,828,421 votes.* 8** Rhodesian prime minister Smith warns that Rhodesia will resist a embargo by neighboring countries with force.** The Race Relations Act becomes the first legislation to address racial discrimination in the United Kingdom.** The Vatican Council closes.* 9 &ndash; Charlie Brown Christmas, the first Peanuts television special, debuts on CBS, quickly becoming an annual tradition.* 15** Free Trade Association (CARIFTA) formed.** Tanzania and Guinea sever relations with the Kingdom.** 6 and 7 perform the first controlled rendezvous in Earth orbit.* 17 &ndash; The British government begins an oil embargo against Rhodesia; the States joins the effort.* 20 &ndash; WFP made a permanent UN agency.* 21** The Union announces that it has shipped rockets to Vietnam.** Soviet scientists condemn Lysenko for pseudoscience.** In West Germany, Adenauer resigns as chairman of the Christian Democratic Party.** A new, 1-hour German-American production of Nutcracker, with an international cast that includes Villella in the title role, makes its U.S. TV debut. It is repeated annually by CBS over the next 3 years, but after that, it is virtually forgotten, until it is issued on DVD in 2009 by Warner Archive.* 22** A coup occurs in Dahomey.** A  limit is imposed on British roads.** Release of Leans film of Doctor Zhivago, starring Sharif and Christie.* 25 &ndash; The Yemeni Unionist Peoples Organisation is founded in Taiz.* 27 &ndash; The British platform Sea Gem collapses in the Sea.* 28 &ndash; Italian Foreign Minister Amintore Fanfani resigns.* 30** President Kaunda of Zambia announces that Zambia and the United Kingdom have agreed on a deadline before which the Rhodesian white government should be ousted.** Marcos becomes of the Philippines.* 31 &ndash; Bokassa takes power in the Africa Republic. Date unknown * Tokyo officially becomes the largest city of the world, taking the lead from York City.(http://geography.about.com/library/weekly/aa011201a.htm)* The for National Academic Awards is established in the UK.* TAT-4 cable goes into operation.* Aborigines are given the vote in Queensland. World population  Births  January * 3 &ndash; A. LaChance, American Author* 4 &ndash; Ormond, British actress* 5** Jones, British footballer-turned-actor** Sjoberg, Swedish high jumper* 6 &ndash; Konnan, Cuban-born professional wrestler* 9 ** Khan, Indian choreographer, film director** Richardson, British actress* 12** Borschevsky, Russian professional ice hockey player (retired)** Zombie, American musician* 14** Fearnley-Whittingstall, British chef** Basayev, Chechen terrorist (d. 2006)** Delissen, Dutch field h