Nikkei_225
thumb|300px|Nikkei 225thumb|300px|Nikkei 225 (USD)The , more commonly called the Nikkei, the Nikkei index, or the Nikkei Stock Average(http://dictionary.cambridge.org/dictionary/british/the-nikkei-index)(http://education.yahoo.com/reference/dictionary/entry/Nikkei) (, , or ), is a market index for the Stock Exchange (TSE). It has been calculated daily by the Keizai Shimbun (Nikkei) newspaper since 1950. It is a average (the unit is yen), and the components are reviewed once a year. Currently, the Nikkei is the most widely quoted average of Japanese equities, similar to the Jones Industrial Average. In fact, it was known as the Nikkei Dow Jones Stock Average from 1975 to 1985.(Nikkei Definition via Wikinvest)The Nikkei 225 began to be calculated on September 7, 1950, retroactively calculated back to May 16, 1949. Since January 2010 the index is updated every 15 seconds during trading sessions.The Nikkei 225 Futures, introduced at Exchange (SGX) in 1986, the Osaka Securities Exchange (OSE) in 1988, Mercantile Exchange (CME) in 1990,  is now an internationally recognized futures index.(Nikkei Net Interactive)The Nikkei average has deviated sharply from the textbook model of stock averages which grow at a steady exponential rate. The average hit its all-time high on December 29, 1989, during the peak of the asset price bubble, when it reached an intra-day high of 38,957.44 before closing at 38,915.87, having grown sixfold during the decade. Subsequently, it lost nearly all these gains, closing at 7,054.98 on March 10, 200981.9% below its peak twenty years earlier.Another major index for the Tokyo Stock Exchange is the Topix.On March 15, 2011, the second working day after the massive earthquake in the northeast part of Japan, the index dropped over 10% to finish at 8605.15, a loss of 1,015 points. This put it at its lowest close since March 10, 2009.Weighting and modificationsStocks are weighted on the Nikkei 225 by giving an equal weighting based on a par value of 50 yen per share. Events such as stock splits, removals and additions of constituents impact upon the effective weighting of individual stocks and the divisor. The Nikkei 225 is designed to reflect the overall market, so there is no specific weighting of industries.Changes to the componentsStocks are reviewed annually and announcements of review results are made in September. Changes, if required, are made at the beginning of October. Changes may also take place at any time if a stock is found to be ineligible (e.g., delisting). All proposed changes will be announced in Nikkeis Japanese newspapers and will appear on NNI.After a stock has been replaced, the divisor is reviewed and modified to ensure a smooth transition of the stock index.ComponentsAs of April 2011, the Nikkei 225 consists of the following companies: (Japanese securities identification code in parentheses)Foods* Ajinomoto Co., Inc. ()* Breweries, Ltd. ()* Tobacco Inc. ()* Kikkoman Corp. ()* Kirin Brewery Co., Ltd. ()* Meiji Holdings Company, Limited ()* Nichirei Corp. ()* Meat Packers, Inc. ()* Seifun Group Inc. ()* Sapporo Holdings Ltd. ()* Holdings Inc. ()Textiles & apparel* Industries, Inc. ()* Teijin Ltd. ()* Industries, Inc. ()* Toyobo Co., Ltd. ()* Unitika, Ltd. ()Pulp & paper* Paper Mills, Ltd. ()* Paper Mills Ltd. ()* Paper Group, Inc. ()* Paper Co., Ltd. ()Chemicals* Kasei Corp. ()* Kagaku Kogyo K.K. ()* Fujifilm Holdings Corp. ()* Kao Corp. ()* Kuraray Co., Ltd. ()* Chemical Holdings Corp. ()* Chemicals, Inc. ()* Kayaku Co., Ltd. ()* Soda Co., Ltd. ()* Chemical Industries, Ltd. ()* Chemical Co., Ltd. ()* Shiseido Co., Ltd. ()* Denko K.K. ()* Chemical Co., Ltd. ()* Tosoh Corp. ()* Industries, Ltd. ()Pharmaceuticals* Pharma Inc. ()* Chugai Pharmaceutical Co., Ltd. ()* Daiichi Sankyo Co., Ltd. ()* Sumitomo Pharma Co., Ltd. ()* Eisai Co., Ltd. ()* Hakko Kirin Co., Ltd. ()* Shionogi & Co., Ltd. ()* Pharmaceutical Company, Ltd. ()Oil & coal products* Oil Corp. ()* Shell Sekiyu K.K. ()Rubber products* B